text:
Ok - this is why you should never trust AI benchmarks.

A recent study compared Opus 4.6 (the latest Claude model) versus Opus 4.5 across 165 different tasks.

The deep research concluded Opus 4.6 did no better than the previous model.

But Opus 4.6 did this with 50% of the cost and 50% of the wall time.

Still massive improvements, just be wary of benchmark headlines.

The best way to determine whether a model is better than previous iterations is to test it for your specific needs.

Anyways, well done to the Anthropic team for this massive cost/wall time reduction.

text:
YC just announced their looking for AI-Native agencies. 

The agency model is about to split into two completely different businesses:

A) Agencies that sell labor
B) Agencies that sell leverage

Only one survives long term.

AI-native agencies don‚Äôt scale by hiring more people.

They scale by building systems that replace people.

The playbook looks like this:

‚Üí Find a workflow clients already overpay for
‚Üí Build an AI tool that does it 10x faster
‚Üí Use services to fund development
‚Üí Turn repeated work into proprietary IP
‚Üí Eventually sell the tool, not the time

The real shift:

Agencies used to be talent businesses.

Now they‚Äôre becoming software companies with cash flow.

Most people will miss this window because they‚Äôre still optimizing delivery instead of building leverage.

That‚Äôs the opportunity.

I'm launching a community of like-minded builders trying to build their own AI-native agency. 

I'm going to share everything I know having built my own 7-figure AI agency.

Looking for motivated people ready to learn & build. 

Drop a comment, I'll personally reach out.
